Hi Colin,

Yes, if the deceptiveness disappears with high-D fitness landscapes, 
then getting stuck doesn&#39;t happen and there is no need to maintain 
diversity. But it is still necessary to protect innovation, if 
complexification is involved, getting to the high dimensions gradually. 
Or perhaps complexification isn&#39;t needed in the first place and the 
search can perform just as good in the high-D space from scratch? I 
think it might be still beneficial to start minimally - it takes less 
computing if anything. Besides, most DNN models are generally of the 
sequential type, a series of layers and that&#39;s all, but with 
complexification there are all sorts of topologies that have nodes 
branching, merging and recurrent connections, and all that can be 
explored. I&#39;m not sure though. Does it even matter with a lot of 
dimensions? It should, because all NN behaviors can be encoded with a 
single huge hidden layer but nobody does this; I assume it doesn&#39;t work 
very well. So the overall topology must be important.

Peter

